<paragraph blockId="42.[313,1269,1396,1580]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">
<emphasis box="[353,486,1460,1484]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">Distribution</emphasis>
. Coast of tropical West Africa from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1045,1131,1460,1484]" name="Senegal" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">Senegal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1177,1264,1460,1484]" name="Angola" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">Angola</collectingCountry>
. Also known from the tropical western Atlantic (Nielsen 
<emphasis box="[966,1023,1492,1516]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">et al.</emphasis>
, 1999).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[313,1269,1396,1580]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254">
On average about 
<quantity box="[569,693,1523,1548]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="4.5" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254" unit="t" value="450.0">450 tonnes</quantity>
of this species are caught in the region each year (
<bibRefCitation author="FAO" box="[324,457,1556,1580]" pageId="42" pageNumber="2254" refId="ref23310" refString="Four species are likely to be found in the Gulf of Guinea (Shipp, 1981) and two were recorded by Irvine from Ghana. On average about 75 tonnes of triggerfishes are reported to be caught in the region each year (FAO, 2000)." type="book" year="2000">FAO, 2000</bibRefCitation>
), making it a significant fishery species.
</paragraph>
